<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-764-928  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 764 928.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  August 9 1990 n1226 p48(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Coast vanishes as BT boat sets sail. (British Telecom abandonsplans for office automation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hill, Simon.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>British Telecom abandons plans to improve its corporate officeautomation strategy, at a proposed cost of 100 million poundssterling.andP;  A new plan is in the works for a more realistic andcost effective system.andP;  The Boat (office automation in BT) projecthas been referred, by operational requirement, to 15 Unix systemsuppliers.andP;  The new system plans signal the eventual demise of theCommon Office Automation System for Telecom (Coast) projectannounced in 1988.andP;  Office automation systems presentlyoperational within BT will be taken into account.andP;  The project mayevolve into a systems integration exercise.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   British Telecommunications PLC (automation).andO;Topic:     ReorganizationOffice AutomationInformation SystemsSystem DesignUNIXStrategic Planning.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>